1. Checkbox

Used when the user can select MULTIPLE options at the same time
Each checkbox is independent of the others
All checkboxes in a group share the same name but different value
type="checkbox" inside an input tag
Example:

<input type="checkbox" id="html" name="skills" value="html" />
<label for="html">HTML</label>




2. Radio Button

Used when the user can select ONLY ONE option from a group
All radio buttons in a group must share the same name
Selecting one automatically deselects the others
type="radio" inside an input tag
Example:

<input type="radio" id="male" name="gender" value="male" />
<label for="male">Male</label>


Key difference from checkbox — checkbox allows many selections, radio allows only one


3. Dropdown

Used when there are many options but only one can be selected
Saves space compared to showing all radio buttons
Uses <select> tag wrapping multiple <option> tags
First option is usually a placeholder with empty value
Example:

html<select name="country">
  <option value="">-- Select Country --</option>
  <option value="australia">Australia</option>
  <option value="india">India</option>
</select>

4. Range

A slider input that lets user pick a value between min and max
Uses min, max, and step attributes
step controls how much it moves per slide
The selected value is not shown automatically — needs JavaScript to display
Example:

<input type="range" name="salary" min="0" max="100" step="5" />




5. Textarea

Used for multi-line text input
Unlike <input>, it has an opening and closing tag
rows controls the visible height
cols controls the visible width
User can resize it by default
Example:

<textarea name="message" rows="4" placeholder="Write here..."></textarea>


Key difference from input text — input is single line, textarea is multi-line


